[normal]Licence Fee Payer
[normal] and to better reflect audiences all around the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Committee will know that the UK TV production sector has benefitted greatly from interventions undertaken by previous governments, firstly to set up Channel 4 and
[normal] S4C as PSBs which, as publisher-broadcasters, commissioned wholly from the UK indie TV sector, and secondly introduced the 25% independent production quota. The addition of a Window of Creative Competition by the BBC 
[normal]in 200
[normal]7,
[normal] along with the protection of indie companies’ IP rights in the 2003 Communications Act, has resulted in a hugely successful international industry. It has also given the Licence F
[normal]e
[normal]e Payer access to a wider range of innovative ideas and fresh talent.
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TAC w
[normal]as encouraged to hear BBC Creative Director Alan Yentob talk at the Edinburgh TV Festival in August of the possibility of the 50% in-house guarantee for BBC in-house producers being removed within five years. TAC hopes this reflects a general understanding
[normal] in the BBC that,
[normal] 
[normal]with TV indie producers winning between 75%-80% of commissions competed for by both in-house and indies, the way forward is to allow more such competition. A good next step might be
[normal] 
[normal]for BBC TV
[normal] to move to a 50% WoCC, and TAC would welcome 
[normal]such a recommendation being made by the Committee.
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In radio, indie production has less scope, with only a 10% quota and additional 10% WoCC in operation. TAC’s producers involved in radio have noted that in the first year of its operation, the radio WoCC s
[normal]aw 80% of the hours on offer won by indie radio companies. This is a clear sign that BBC Radio could benefit from additional competition. TAC would therefore support the independent radio production sector in its call for a 25% quota and 25% WoCC to allow 
[normal]the sector to grow and provide more creative competition, again for the benefit of the Licence Fee Payer and the 
[normal]UK
[normal] economy.
[normal]How have the BBC’s commercial activities during the current Charter fitted with the BBC’s public purposes and have they achieved an[bold] adequate return for licence fee payers? What should be the aims, scope and scale of such activities beyond 2016?[bold]14.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is fair for the BBC to be able to maximise the value of the content it produces – revenue from international sales, secondary channel deals
[normal], DV
[normal]D
[normal]s
[normal],
[normal] downloads 
[normal]and so on 
[normal]can be used to increase the content budget. Of course the BBC should always have an eye to whether
[normal] or not
[normal] it is adversely affecting commercial organisations through 
[normal]such activity. It should also not use the fact that it owns the
[normal] IP to in-house produced content as a reason 
[normal]to restrict 
[normal]open
[normal]ing
[normal] up its commissioning to competition from independent producers.
[normal] The more successful and high-quality BBC programmes are, the more revenue they can sometimes generate, meaning everybody – the BBC, the indie producer and the Licence Fee Payer – benefits.
[normal]What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new way[bold]s of distributing content?[bold]15.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is important for the BBC to make sure it has its content 
[normal]on whatever platform the LF payer chooses to access it 
[normal]– eg online, on mobile 
[normal]and
[normal] so on. However in doing so it must always ensure it is allowing the producers of that c
[normal]ontent to benefit from the use of their intellectual property
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?[bold]In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary [bold]of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?[bold]16.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As long as there is a fundamentally flexible nature to the BBC’s structure it should be able to deal with new changes and challenges within the current Charter system
[normal].
[normal]17.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TAC believes it is very important for the Secretary of State to have ultimate responsibility for the Public Service broadcasters – for this reason we are unhappy with 
[normal]the BBC Trust ha
[normal]ving
[normal] the power to 
[normal]withdraw 
[normal]its 
[normal]f
