[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]S4C is a unique broadcaster and not 
[normal]in any way 
[normal]part of the BBC
[normal]. 
[normal]It plays a unique role in the everyday lives of the people of 
[normal]Wales
[normal] as well as making a progressive and key contribution to 
[normal]Wales
[normal], its economy, and the Welsh language.  
[normal]Its publisher-broadcaster model means 
[normal]that 
[normal]it commissions all of its content externally
[normal], from 
[normal]the
[normal] Welsh independent production sector. 
[normal]It also has a remit of its own to commission programming that meets with the unique requirements and taste of a particular audience namely the people of 
[normal]Wales
[normal], be they fluent Welsh speakers, learners or those
[normal] who aspire to learn
[normal] the language
[normal].  This includes high-level content focusing, issues of great concern to the people of Wales, from the Welsh language to heritage, culture and music, Wales’ agricultural heritage as well as factual programmes,
[normal] sport,
[normal] high-q
[normal]uality drama or reflecting the issues specific to different parts of Wales.  
[normal]It provides invaluable and unique provision for children – 
[normal]from pre-school to teenagers 
[normal](content originated and produced in 
[normal]Wales
[normal]) and it also provides content for Welsh language 
[normal]learners. As a national broadcaster it has been vital in enabling a creative sector to be based all around 
[normal]Wales
[normal] – in the capital city 
[normal]Cardiff
[normal] and also in Caernarfon, in 
[normal]Swansea
[normal] and in Llanelli. 
