[normal]30.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TAC 
[normal]considers
[normal] it essential that:
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]If the plurality of Welsh PSB broadcasting, along 
[normal]with the Welsh language and the independent production sector are to be allowed to flourish, the above measures are essential. If it is not possible within the current arrangement to ensure this editorial and operational independence, TAC believes that the
[normal] Committee should examine whether or not it would be preferable to allocate a specific proportion of the TV Licence Fee directly to S4C, entirely separately from the Licence Fee money that is the 
[normal]responsibility of the BBC Trust. This would have the added a
[normal]dvantage of restoring full operational and managerial independence to S4C.
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]TAC is very aware of the contrasting arguments on the merits of such 'top-slicing’ and is not necessarily saying it would support this proposal as a first option, but it is importan
[normal]t to make sure above all else that S4C continues to be able to operate effectively as a separate entity with sufficient guaranteed funding to fulfil its objectives.
[normal] 
[normal]If it cannot do so within the current arrangement then 
[normal]other arrangements including top-sli
[normal]cing the Licence Fee ought to be considered
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]33.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]A plurality of broadcasting is as important in 
[normal]Wales
[normal] as it is elsewhere. S4C also contributes greatly to the Welsh economy – an independent report published earlier this year showed that every pound spent in th
[normal]e Welsh creative industries generated nearly £2 worth of economic growth
[normal]. S4C provides high-quality programmes unique in its character and content. It must not be allowed to be damaged by the lack of a sustainable funding arrangement or risk of losing its
[normal] editorial and managerial independence.
